{
  "query": "To reduce the impacts of nitrogen pollution in UK heathlands, is prescribed burning more effective than mowing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies from the UK, prescribed burning and mowing appear to be equally effective for reducing impacts of nitrogen pollution in heathlands. One randomized, replicated, controlled study in the UK found that prescribed burning to reduce the impact of nitrogen deposition did not alter the shoot length of common heather or the number of purple moor grass seedlings compared to mowing (Action 1670). Similarly, a controlled study in the UK found that burning to reduce the concentration of pollutants in a heathland affected by nitrogen pollution did not alter the cover or shoot length of heather relative to areas that were mowed (Action 1670). From the mowing perspective, a randomized, replicated, controlled study in the UK found that mowing to reduce the impact of nitrogen deposition did not alter shoot length of common heather or the number of purple moor grass seedlings (Action 1669). Another controlled study in the UK found that mowing a heathland affected by nitrogen pollution did not alter the cover or shoot length of heather compared to areas where prescribed burning was used (Action 1669). These studies indicate that neither prescribed burning nor mowing showed superior effectiveness over the other for reducing nitrogen pollution impacts on heather vegetation characteristics in UK heathlands.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1670",
    "1669"
  ]
}

