{"query": "What are the most beneficial interventions for restoring shrubland vegetation after a fire?", "summary": "Based on the available evidence, the most beneficial interventions for restoring shrubland vegetation after fire include both passive and active approaches. Allowing shrubland to regenerate without active management was found to be effective, with five before-and-after trials in the USA, UK, and Norway showing increased shrub cover or biomass, and one replicated, paired site comparison in the USA finding that sites allowed to recover without active restoration had similar shrub cover to unburned areas (Action 1679). Two replicated, randomized, controlled, before-and-after trials in Spain and Portugal found increases in the cover of woody plant species, and one replicated, before-and-after study in South Africa found that the height of three protea species increased after recovery from fire (Action 1679).

Active restoration interventions show mixed results. Adding mulch followed by seeding with shrub seeds increased the seedling abundance of one of seven shrub species in one randomized, controlled study in the USA, though it did not reduce grass cover (Action 1650). Hydroseeding (spraying a slurry of seed, mulch and water) showed variable effectiveness, with one controlled study in Spain finding increased overall plant cover in most cases, while another study found no alteration in vegetation cover (Action 3412). Adding mulch before sowing seeds increased the cover of target plant species in one replicated, controlled study in Germany and increased the number of seedlings in most cases in one replicated, controlled study in Canada (Action 3425). Using erosion blankets after seeding showed mixed results, with one study in Spain finding increased plant species richness and plant density, while two studies in the USA found no alteration in vegetation cover (Action 3431). 

Prescribed fire for maintaining or restoring disturbance was shown to reduce tree/shrub cover in two replicated studies in fens in the USA and UK, and increased plant species richness or diversity in two replicated, controlled studies in the USA and New Zealand (Action 1763).", "action_ids": ["1679","1650","3412","3425","3431","1763"]}

